data$date <- as.Date(data$date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
ts_data <- ts(data$number, start = c(1998, 1), frequency = 12)
model <- auto.arima(ts_data)
summary(model)
## Series: ts_data 
## ARIMA(5,0,1) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ar3      ar4     ar5      ma1      mean
##       1.1115  -0.0936  -0.0396  -0.0450  0.0443  -0.8394  108.4132
## s.e.  0.0200   0.0191   0.0187   0.0186  0.0138   0.0159   13.6770
## 
## sigma^2 = 23652:  log likelihood = -41654.48
## AIC=83324.96   AICc=83324.98   BIC=83379.14
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                      ME     RMSE      MAE  MPE MAPE     MASE         ACF1
## Training set 0.04986443 153.7076 84.42945 -Inf  Inf 0.726836 -0.001360449
#The ARIMA(5,0,1) model means it used 5 past values and 1 past error to make predictions. The model found an average value around 108 and gave a good fit overall. Some accuracy numbers like RMSE and MAE look reasonable, but MAPE is infinite, which might be because there are zero values in the data.
checkresiduals(model)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(5,0,1) with non-zero mean
## Q* = 95.829, df = 18, p-value = 1.278e-12
## 
## Model df: 6.   Total lags used: 24
forecasted <- forecast(model, h=5)


plot(forecasted)

accuracy(model)
